Asclepias fascicularis is commonly known as narrow-leaf milkweed.
It is a perennial plant and belongs to the Asclepiadaceae family.
The stem of Asclepias fascicularis is erect and can grow up to 3 feet tall.
The leaves are long, narrow, and pointed and have a smooth surface.
The flowers of Asclepias fascicularis are pink or pale purple and bloom from mid-summer to fall.
It is commonly found in dry, open areas such as fields, meadows, and along roadsides.
Asclepias fascicularis is an important host plant for monarch butterflies and its nectar attracts pollinators such as bees and butterflies.
